Barbara: jsooudi(572): I think the people commenting on this site would react entirely differently were they seated next to an allergic child on a plane.
Barbara: jsooudi(572): Of course they would refrain from eating peanuts for a few hours if they knew it would hurt someone they were looking in the face.
Barbara: jsooudi(572): But I am sympathetic to individuals who are unhappy with yet another discomfort inflicted on air travelers.
Barbara: jsooudi(572): This restriction is designed to protect people with allergies from the airlines callous disregard for cleanliness and for our safety, not from our fellow passengers.
Barbara: jsooudi(572): "Hi.  My name is Steven.  I am 4 years old.
Barbara: jsooudi(572): I am allergic to peanuts, eggs and cow milk.
Barbara: jsooudi(572): If I eat a peanut I'll get sick.
Barbara: jsooudi(572): I ate a nut one time and got a big bump on my lip and it swelled up and it was hard to breathe.
Barbara: jsooudi(572): It was scary and my dad gave me some medicine that made it better.
Barbara: jsooudi(572): I would like for them to not give out peanuts so I won't get sick because I'm allergic.
Barbara: jsooudi(572): Everybody should drink Sprite and eat Pringles and Pretzels."
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): My child is 2 years old and he is severely allergic to peanuts, tree nuts, egg and milk.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): My son has reacted to airborne particles from someone opening a bag of nuts near him.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): My husband and I used to be world traveler's and dreamed of traveling with our son.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): It is heartbreaking to think that our child will not get to experience the world, or if he does it may cost him his life.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): What about when he gets older and his job requires him to fly across the country in a weekend?
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): Should he have to risk his life so he can work in his possible future dream job?
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): This is a disability, no question about it.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): We are talking about being in the air with peanut particles being circulated through the cabin and possible no place to land for hours.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): An EpiPen only last 15 minutes.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): Peanut allergy is unpredictable.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): The first reaction could be mild
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): and the second could cause your blood pressure to drop like a rocket, your throat to close up and your heart to stop beating.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): Yes, we carry Epipens everywhere we go,
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): but even 10 wouldn't be enough on an airplane.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): I know that airplane or not you could be somewhere where peanuts are opened.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): The point is, you can't leave an airplane and get away from the peanut dust.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): You can leave other areas and get away from it.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): Also, we do not chose to be anywhere we know there will be a lot of people eating peanuts,
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): like ball games or restaurants that have them on the floor of their establishments.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): It's not going to cost you your job if you choose not to go to a ball game or certain restaurant.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): It will if you keep refusing to travel and the job requires that.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): I don't know anyone who will DIE if they don't have peanuts/peanut dust,
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): but I know plenty of people who would DIE if they do have peanuts or breathe in peanut dust.
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): I support a ban on all peanuts and peanut products on airplanes
Barbara: FoodAllergyMom(574): and an announcement to all passengers asking them to refrain from eating peanut products during the flight.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): As a parent of a child with severe lifethreatening allergies to peanuts and treenuts, the thought of getting on an airplane today is frightening.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): So much so, that it is strictly avoided.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): It is not worth risking my child's life to fly on an airplane.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): A recent study reveals that 1 in 3 airplane reactions was anaphylaxis
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): (Allergic Living Magazine).
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): I don't like those odds.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): The substitution of cashews, walnuts, or other tree nuts is not a viable option,
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): as they pose the same risks as peanuts.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): A large number of people who are allergic to peanuts are also allergic to tree nuts,
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): plus they are typically processed in a plant that also processes peanuts.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): If there were a ban on peanut and tree nut products on flights, it would open the world to my son.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): He didn't choose to be allergic,
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): but he is.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): So true.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): We are not talking about sensitivity, being offended, not liking the smell, etc.;
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): we are talking about life.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): There are a lot of things that are banned from airplanes that can cause death to someone.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): In the case of my son, a peanut can have the same result.
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): I urge the DOT to issue the ban,
Barbara: AllergyDad(577): and make traveling safe for everyone.
Barbara: howie(351): First, stop reading that propaganda magazine.
Barbara: howie(351): Publications like that only serve to create fear in minds like yours.
Barbara: howie(351): Second, how old is your kid?
Barbara: howie(351): If under 5, relax the sensitivity will probably go away by the time he is 5.
Barbara: howie(351): Third, go to a real doctor  not an allergist and see if there is really even a problem at all.
Barbara: howie(351): This supposed plague of food allergies is the result of very clever advertising by this profession of pseudoscientists.
Barbara: howie(351): Allergists are not doctors.
Barbara: howie(351): I sincerely doubt you "know plenty of people who will die if they do have peanuts or breathe in peanut dust".
Barbara: howie(351): Almost noone is actually that allergic.
Barbara: howie(351): Lot's of people think they are much worse off than they really are.
Barbara: howie(351): Methinks you have an agenda.
Barbara: howie(351): Highly suspicious that the child of a physician who is hyper aware of bad things that can happen coincidentally has not one, but three life threatening allergies.
Barbara: howie(351): Have you heard of Munchasen by Proxy?
Barbara: howie(351): Do you realize that most kids have mild reactions to various food items that they invariably grow out of by the age of 5?
Barbara: howie(351): Food allergies have to be the most overblown imagined health problem of our time.
Barbara: howie(351): Hypochondriacs all.
